c/Workflow disqualified because behavior is purely daemon/filesystem resilience.","test_description":"Start daemon watching a real directory, delete the directory while daemon keeps running, recreate it at the same path, add a new file, and assert the new file is processed without restarting the daemon process.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.03,"Integration":0.07,"System":0.9,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"When multiple files arrive at the same time, they are processed in the order determined by their creation timestamps.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Ordering depends on real file arrival timing and filesystem timestamp metadata/resolution under near-simultaneous writes. MOCK-MISS: queue ordering bugs can emerge from interaction between watcher events, stat metadata, and scheduler. REAL-INFRA/MOCK-HIDE: in-process mocks usually provide ideal timestamps and deterministic event order, hiding real races/timestamp granularity issues. REJECTION-GATE: Integration considered, but behavior text specifically ties order to creation timestamps at arrival time, which is a real filesystem property; Agentic/Workflow disqualified (no AI dependence).","test_description":"With daemon running on a real watched directory, create several files in rapid succession (or concurrently), capture their actual creation timestamps from filesystem metadata, and assert processing/output order matches timestamp order (including defined tie-break rule if timestamps collide).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.3,"System":0.6,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"A file that is still being written to when the arrival event fires is not picked up for processing until writing is complete.","minimum_level":"System","justification":"Failure boundary is real partial-write timing between producer and watcher-triggered consumer. REAL-INFRA: requires true filesystem write-in-progress behavior and event timing. MOCK-HIDE: mocked 'file ready' signals often skip lock/flush/chunked-write realities and can falsely pass. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) yes, OS/fs timing is required, so Integration is too low. REJECTION-GATE: Agentic/Workflow disqualified by behavior text focused on file write completion gating.","test_description":"Start daemon, begin writing a large file in chunks with delays so arrival event fires before final close, assert no processing occurs during writes, then close writer and assert processing starts only after completion.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.05,"Integration":0.15,"System":0.8,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}}]}
